-- UK's Serious Fraud Office probes banks' loan schemes -Times
-- By Karen Rebelo in Bangalore
-- Sun Aug 17, 2014 07:16PM EDT
-- None



Aug 17 (Reuters) - The Serious Fraud Office is looking into allegations of high street banks misusing government schemes designed to boost lending to small businesses, the Times reported on Sunday.

The Times reported that the UK's main anti-fraud agency is investigating banks' use of the Enterprise Finance Guarantee, and its predecessor, the Small Firms Loan Guarantee Scheme in relation to small business customers. The newspaper it had seen correspondence that showed the SFO was studying allegations about alleged abuse by lenders.  The paper said the SFO has yet to announce whether it will launch a formal investigation. (http://thetim.es/1ApCo9d)